com.apriori.collections

Class HamtMap<K,V>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractMap<K,V>
      • com.apriori.collections.HamtMap<K,V>
  • Type Parameters:
    K - the type of keys in the map
    V - the type of value in the map
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.util.Map<K,V>

    public class HamtMap<K,V>
extends java.util.AbstractMap<K,V>
implements java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable
    An implementation of Map that uses a hash array-mapped trie (HAMT). Under the hood, this structure is the same as an ArrayMappedBitwiseTrie except that the key bits come from a key's hash value. Like a HashMap, a linked list is used to store values whose keys' hash values collide. But collisions are far less likely than in a HashMap because the full 32 bits of hash value are used (vs. hash value modulo array size, which is typically far lower cardinality than the full 32 bits).

    Since this structure doesn't use a fixed size array for the mappings, it never pays a penalty for resizing internal structures and re-hashing all of its contents (unlike a HashMap). Also, since the full 32 bits of hash code are used to store entries, no alternative hashing is needed.

    A HamtMap supports both null keys and values, and it supports all optional operations in the Map interface. This implementation is not thread-safe and its iterators will attempt to fail fast, by throwing a ConcurrentModificationException if improper concurrency is detected.
